{"title":"Graph Rationalization with Environment-based Augmentations","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Graph rationale identification for graph property prediction struggles with small datasets and typically discards the non-causal environment, leading to poor generalization; prior methods (e.g., DIR) rely on distribution interventions and explicit subgraph construction, which are data-hungry and inefficient.","method":"Introduce environment-based data augmentations tailored for rationalization: (1) environment removal (train on rationale-only representations) and (2) environment replacement (for each graph i, combine its rationale with environment representations from other batch graphs j to create B−1 virtual samples). These augmentations are performed in latent space using an aggregation function (e.g., elementwise sum) to form h_(i,j) and are trained so that predictions for both h_r,i and h_(i,j) match the original label y_i, with losses L_rem and L_rep jointly optimized."},{"problem":"Explicitly decoding/encoding rationale and augmented subgraphs is computationally prohibitive and mixing subgraphs across graphs is technically difficult, which limits scalability and coherence of learned rationales.","method":"Propose GREA, a latent-space framework that avoids explicit subgraph construction. A separator (GNN1+MLP1) produces node-level rationale probabilities m; a second encoder (GNN2) yields contextual node embeddings H. Rationale and environment graph representations are computed via masked pooling (h^(r)=Σ(m⊙H), h^(e)=Σ((1−m)⊙H)), and augmented representations are formed by aggregating h^(r)_i with h^(e)_j across the batch. Training alternates between separator and predictor, includes a size regularizer L_reg to control rationale size, and uses rationale-only predictions at inference, yielding higher efficiency and accuracy."},{"problem":"Edge-selection-based rationalization can produce fragmented, incoherent subgraphs that lose atomic context, reducing interpretability and accuracy on real molecule/polymer data.","method":"Learn node-level rationale masks with a lightweight rationale GNN and gating MLP (separator) to select coherent node sets as rationales. The separator gates node embeddings and aggregates them with scatter-add to obtain rationale and environment representations, while a size regularization (gamma) encourages concise rationales. Case studies show the method yields chemically coherent functional groups and improved predictions (e.g., O2 permeability) compared to edge-based selection."}]}
